ğŸ› ï¸ Step-by-Step: Pentesting Port 111 Using nmap
ğŸ” 1. Basic Scan for Open Port
Check that port 111 is open and identify the service:

bash
Copy
Edit
nmap -sV -p 111 <target_ip>
Expected output:

bash
Copy
Edit
111/tcp open  rpcbind  2-4 (RPC #100000)
ğŸ”§ 2. Use NSE Script: rpcinfo
This mimics rpcinfo -p to enumerate all registered RPC services:

bash
Copy
Edit
nmap -sV -sT -p 111 --script=rpcinfo <target_ip>
Example output:

bash
Copy
Edit
PORT    STATE SERVICE
111/tcp open  rpcbind
| rpcinfo:
|   program version    port/proto  service
|   100000  2,3,4       111/tcp    rpcbind
|   100003  2,3         2049/tcp   nfs
|   100005  1,2,3       32771/tcp  mountd
ğŸ›¡ï¸ If you see nfs, mountd, rquotad, or similar services: they must be reviewed for misconfigurations.

ğŸ—„ï¸ 3. Scan for NFS Exports (if NFS is listed)
If NFS is running (usually on port 2049), list exported file systems:

bash
Copy
Edit
nmap -p 111,2049 --script=nfs-showmount <target_ip>
Example:

wasm
Copy
Edit
| nfs-showmount:
|   /export/data Everyone
ğŸ”¥ Danger: If "Everyone" can mount a share, it's a serious misconfiguration.

ğŸ’£ 4. Check for Readable Shares (Mount Attempt)
bash
Copy
Edit
showmount -e <target_ip>
Then try to mount it (on a Linux box):

bash
Copy
Edit
mkdir /mnt/test
mount -t nfs <target_ip>:/export/data /mnt/test
ls /mnt/test
âŒ If a share mounts without authentication, you have a major security issue.

ğŸ›‘ 5. Check for Vulnerable Services (Old RPC Vulns)
You can extend nmap with:

bash
Copy
Edit
nmap -sV -p 111 --script=rpcinfo,rpc-grind <target_ip>
rpc-grind: Tries to identify unlisted or hidden services.

Look for services running on high ports like 32771 or 32768 â€” common with mountd, statd, rquotad.
